&#xa0;
[normal]Written evidence from the Police and Crime Commissioner for Avon and Somerset [CST0053][bold]&#xa0;[bold]I write to provide information in support of the Public Administration Select Committee’s inquiry into the accuracy of 
[normal]crime statistics[bold]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The issue of crime recording and data integrity remains a
[normal]n important focus for Avon and Somerset Constabulary, and I very much welcome the review that is underway.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.1. [bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold] What, if any, targets do you set for your police force?[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]1.1.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]As part of my Police and Crime Plan, I have set the ambition of becomin
[normal]g a top performing force across all of my priority areas by 2017.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] This is underpinned by nine measures that provide an indication of our position and direction of travel. The measures are sourced from a mix of police recorded crime statistics, national an
[normal]d local perception surveys and criminal justice outcome data – as shown in the table below:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Approach to Monitoring Police and Crime Ambition Areas: 2014-17
